DTSA 5509 Final Project¶

Project Topic¶

In this notebook, we will create and examine models to detect breast cancer, using the Breast Cancer Wisconsin (Diagnostic) Data Set found here: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/uciml/breast-cancer-wisconsin-data. Each of its 569 records provides a set of features computed from a digitized image of a fine needle aspirate of a breast mass, describing characteristics of the cell nuclei present in the image. Each record also includes that patient's diagnosis.

Project Data¶

The Breast Cancer Wisconsin (Diagnostic) Data Set can be found here: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/uciml/breast-cancer-wisconsin-data. It is 569 records x 33 columns (30 features, 1 y-value, 1 id, 1 unnamed NaN).

Dataset columns:¶

(With descriptions when included by the source)

  • id
  • diagnosis - The diagnosis of breast tissues (M = malignant, B = benign)
  • radius_mean - mean of distances from center to points on the perimeter
  • texture_mean - standard deviation of gray-scale values
  • perimeter_mean - mean size of the core tumor
  • area_mean
  • smoothness_mean - mean of local variation in radius lengths
  • compactness_mean - mean of perimeter^2 / area - 1.0
  • concavity_mean - mean of severity of concave portions of the contour
  • concave points_mean - mean for number of concave portions of the contour
  • symmetry_mean
  • fractal_dimension_mean
  • radius_se
  • texture_se
  • perimeter_se
  • area_se
  • smoothness_se
  • compactness_se
  • concavity_se
  • concave points_se
  • symmetry_se
  • fractal_dimension_se
  • radius_worst
  • texture_worst
  • perimeter_worst
  • area_worst
  • smoothness_worst
  • compactness_worst
  • concavity_worst
  • concave points_worst
  • symmetry_worst
  • fractal_dimension_worst
  • Unnamed: 32

The wide gap between the max and 75% values in many columns signify distant outliers. We will need to find a way to limit their effect.

But first, many of these factor columns have names that suggest correlation. Let's pull off and save the diagnosis column, then check the factors' correlation numbers.

A smaller set of 0.94 or higher includes

  • radius_se
  • perimeter_se
  • area_se

We will keep these in mind later to see whether we can drop some of those features to make a more flexible model.

Outlier detection¶

Next, we will look for columns with values more than 2 * IQR from the 25% or 75% values.

In [4]:
descFrame = bcdf.describe()

# describe() returns info for only numeric columns
featureNames = descFrame.columns
rowMin = descFrame.loc[["min"]]
row25 = descFrame.loc[["25%"]]
row75 = descFrame.loc[["75%"]]
rowMax = descFrame.loc[["max"]]
rowLength = descFrame.count(axis = 1)

for n in featureNames:
    val75 = row75[n].item()
    val25 = row25[n].item()
    IQR = val75 - val25
    minFence = val25 - (IQR * 2)
    if minFence < 0:
        minFence = 0
    maxFence = val75 + (IQR * 2)
    if rowMin[n].item() < minFence:
        print(n, "low outlier")
    if rowMax[n].item() > maxFence:
        print(n, "high outlier")

We will deal with this by going back to the original data set and limiting its high values by substituting the "high fence" value (the 75% value + 2 times the IQR) for all outliers higher than that fence.

In [7]:
# Same as above, now with corrective action
for n in featureNames:
    val75 = row75[n].item()
    val25 = row25[n].item()
    IQR = val75 - val25
    maxFence = val75 + (IQR * 2)
    
    # Now substitute the fences for the outliers
    bcdf[n] = np.where(bcdf[n] > maxFence, maxFence, bcdf[n])
    
bcdf.describe()

Logical regression¶

Now let's try out first model, logistic regression.

In [10]:

LSVC¶

Let's try a Linear Support Vector Classification model for the data. After a first attempt, we see a warning that "Liblinear failed to converge". Online comments, especially at StackOverflow, suggest this warning should not be ignored, and is fixed by normalizing the features.

In [12]:

# MixMaxScaler.transform returns a numpy array

Non-linear SVC¶

Let's try a third model against this dataset. After checking SVC with default values, we'll tweak the C and gamma settings to see if we can find one that produces better accuracy than Linear SVC.

In [14]:
nlsvm = None

nlsvm = SVC(gamma = 1) # default kernel is rbf, default C = 1
scores = cross_val_score(nlsvm, X_train, y_train)
print("1 cross-val mean-accuracy: ", np.mean(scores))

grid = None
thisSVM = SVC() # with defaults
valuesC = []
valuesGamma = []
for i in range(-5, 6):
    newValue = 2**i
    valuesC.append(newValue)
    valuesGamma.append(newValue)
cgGrid = {"C": valuesC, "gamma": valuesGamma}

searchedGrid = GridSearchCV(thisSVM, cgGrid, cv = 3)
searchedGrid.fit(X_train, y_train)

print("Best mean_accuracy = ", searchedGrid.best_score_)
print("Using the parameters ", searchedGrid.best_params_)

grid = searchedGrid

Tweaking the best of three models¶

The best model so far is the squared_hinge version of LSVC. Let's see whether there is another value of C that will produce better accuracy.

In [29]:
bestC = 1
bestAccuracy = 0

i = 0.1
while i < 11:
    tempLSVC = LinearSVC(C = i, loss = "squared_hinge", random_state = 1)
    tempLSVC = tempLSVC.fit(X_train, y_train)
    tempPredArray = tempLSVC.predict(X_test)
    tempAccuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, tempPredArray)
    if tempAccuracy > bestAccuracy:
        bestAccuracy = tempAccuracy
        bestC = i
    i = i + 0.1
        
print("For accuracy, the best C is ", bestC)
print("which produced an accuracy of ", bestAccuracy)
print("But from there, accuracy is identical.")
print("For example, the last C tested was 11")
print("which also produced an accuracy of ", tempAccuracy)

For accuracy, the best C is  0.4
which produced an accuracy of  0.9824561403508771
But from there, accuracy is identical.
For example, the last C tested was 11
which also produced an accuracy of  0.9824561403508771

The answer is No. Within a wide range, different values of C do not change the model's accuracy score.

Discussion¶

Let's go back to an idea from the start of this process. With so many strongly correlated features, will the best model produce the same or better results after dropping duplicative features?

In [30]:
# In the first set of correlated features, retain area_mean 
bcdf.drop(['radius_mean'], axis = 1, inplace = True)
bcdf.drop(['perimeter_mean'], axis = 1, inplace = True)
bcdf.drop(['radius_worst'], axis = 1, inplace = True)
bcdf.drop(['perimeter_worst'], axis = 1, inplace = True)
bcdf.drop(['area_worst'], axis = 1, inplace = True)

# In the second set of correlated features, retain area_se 
bcdf.drop(['radius_se'], axis = 1, inplace = True)
bcdf.drop(['perimeter_se'], axis = 1, inplace = True)

# Now split them again and check the number of features
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(bcdf, diag, test_size = 0.2, random_state = 1)

print(X_train.shape, X_test.shape)
print(y_train.shape, y_test.shape)

The accuracy, precision, and recall scores for the 23-column dataset are identical to the results for the full 30-column dataset. This smaller model should be more flexible for future examinations of similar data.

Conclusion¶

It is possible to create numerous models to effectively predict breast cancer diagnoses based on the Breast Cancer Wisconsin (Diagnostic) Data Set. Although all of the examined models are accurate, some models are more accurate than others. In particular, the Squared Hinge version of the Linear Support Vector Classification produced the most accurate predictions of the test data. Almost any value of the C hyperparameter allows this result.

Many of the features in the Wisconsin dataset are highly correlated. Removing all but one feature in each of two tightly bunched sets had no discernible effect on the accuracy of the model. Therefore, use of the reduced, 23-feature model is recommended for more flexible fitting and reduced processing time.
